<font color="#FF0000">MRPARSON! WITH ALL DUE RESPECT</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 11 18:48:48 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Dear Mr. Parson:<br><br>
Your letter frightens me.  It is so safe for you to put your words out there and sactimoniously believe that you have all the answers.  It is your tone and one sided assessment of the situation that reflects the mind-set that tarnished the intention and escalated the pain.  Vietnam is no longer an issue for pseudo-intellectuals, it has become an issue of raw emotion needing to heal and be remembered.<br><br>
It seems as though you have lived a life which never caused doubt, confusion or regret.  Forgive me if that is not the case, but my judgement of you is based on your letter, where you have made blanket statements and generalities.  I too may protest the WAR, but I would never degrade the human sacrifice of life.  I would like to know more about you, in hopes that I may understand you, but I am afraid that there are too many graves and too many tormented dreams that deserve it more. 
<p><code>-- jdickers@maryville.edu  (Joan C. Dickerson) </code><p>


